icdarUrn":"752399_Beach_huts.jpg","width":"380"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/12/19/1387456361181/MG3-008.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"PR","altText":"MG3","height":"276","credit":"PR","caption":"MG3: the famous British marque is back.","picdarUrn":"752399_Beach_huts.jpg","width":"460"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/12/19/1387456361181/MG3-008.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"PR","altText":"MG3","height":"276","credit":"PR","caption":"MG3: the famous British marque is back.","picdarUrn":"752399_Beach_huts.jpg","width":"460"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-425384588","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/12/19/1387456355130/MG3-003.jpg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","source":"PR","altText":"MG3","height":"84","credit":"PR","caption":"MG3: the famous British marque is back.","picdarUrn":"752399_Beach_huts.jpg","width":"140"}}]}],"rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"technology","webTitle":"MG3: car review | Martin Love","references":[],"webPublicationDate":"2013-12-29T10:30:00Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"732","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3ybe7","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/12/19/1387456355130/MG3-003.jpg","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p><strong>Price £8,399</strong><br /><strong>MPG 48.7</strong><br /><strong>Top speed 108mph</strong></p><p>The MG is back, sort of. No other two letters conjure up so immediately an image of fun, affordable, sporty motoring. Still based in Longbridge, but now owned by the massive <a href=\"http://www.saicmotor.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Chinese manufacturer SAIC</a>, the marque tentatively made its reappearance on British roads last year with the unspeakably dull <a href=\"http://mg.co.uk/mg6/?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=cpc&amp;utm_campaign=MG6&amp;utm_term=mg6%20-e&amp;atlassearch=paid\" title=\"\">MG6</a> – a bargain-basement Mondeo wannabe which managed to sell a paltry 300 motors. Where's the fun in that? Now we have the more promising <a href=\"http://mg.co.uk/mg3/\" title=\"\">MG3</a> – which is half the size but at least twice as good.</p><p>With images of sportsters, scarves and blonde hair floating before my eyes I ring my friend Guy to tell him MG's news (I did have other things to say to him, too, <em>actually</em>). He was once the proud owner of an MG roadster back in the 80s. It was an unhealthy sludge colour with brown seats and a beige fabric roof, but we all loved it. For a couple of summers it was our trump card in the dating game. Who am I kidding? It was our only card.</p><p>\"Oh no,\" Guy groans. \"That car was a pile of rusting crap that cost me a&nbsp;fortune.\" Would he like to come for a test drive in MG's new entry-level hatchback? There's a pause. And then: \"No, of course not.\"</p><p>So I'm on my own. But the MG3 still wants to have fun. It's not glamorous in the way you remember an MG being, and to the young motorist who it's aimed at, the letters now mean something quite different from <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MG_Cars\" title=\"\">Morris Garages</a>. My teenage son informs me they now stand for Morning Glory. As in: \"Bruv, man's mum came in and almost saw the MG – it was peak!\" Nevertheless, the  MG3 is a sharp-looking car. It's mostly built in China, with the final assembly taking place in the UK, but it is styled and designed in Longbridge, where the company employs about 400 engineers. You can still fly the flag if you want to.</p><p>The car has clean lines and a&nbsp;pleasing, bold face. But it's hard for a vehicle to stand out in the super-competitive supermini class. Squint and it looks a bit Fabia, or maybe a bit Yaris, oh and definitely a&nbsp;bit Fiesta. MG has got round this by offering more personalisation options than really make sense. They claim the car has over a million possible permutations. The graphic packs cost up to £225 and you can put emoticon stickers on the roof, or a&nbsp;decal that looks like a tyre burnout. My test car seemed to be covered in fake fallen leaves – which drove me mad, as it was covered in real ones, too, being winter, and I kept trying to pick them off. Did it look cool? I'm not its 20-something target, but I think not.  I asked the boy again: \"Nah, it just makes you look like a real beg.\"</p><p>The base car starts at an amazingly cheap £8,399. Even if you go for the top-spec model, which includes an iPod connection, DAB radio, aircon, Bluetooth, parking sensor, airbags, LED running lights, cruise control and steering wheel audio controls, you still get a pound change from 10 grand.</p><p>The car handles well, but it's let down by the engine. It's a 1.5-litre petrol, which for this size of car is far too big. You could live with that, but this one whines and wheezes and you have to rev it hard to make any headway. The large engine means emissions are high, though consumption is reasonable. But no one in a car this size wants to pay £140 road tax when far bigger cars attract close to nothing.</p><p>This MG could be up there with the best cheap cars – but not until it gets a new engine. Either way, it's great to see MG rising again…</p><h2>Life-sized Scalextric on the streets of London</h2><figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DITjqRmZ7JA\">  <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/DITjqRmZ7JA?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen>  </iframe></figure><p><br />Scalextric (owned by Hornby Hobbies) has been working with Scorch London and Renault UK to produce their latest stunt video, showing two electric cars racing on a giant Scalextric track in London. The electric Renault Zoe vehicles were modified to mimic real Scalextric cars with competition winners racing against each other using remote controllers in a helicopter. It's a long way from the track on your parents' living room floor, but the old \"racing on rails\" feel still seems to be there…</p><p>Email Martin at <a href=\"http://martin.love@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\">martin.love@observer.co.uk</a> or follow him on Twitter at <a href=\"https://twitter.com/martinlove166\" title=\"\">@MartinLove166</a></p>","internalOctopusCode":"8461090","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-12-29T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"true","internalPageCode":"2016070","internalContentCode":"425380821","publication":"The Observer","trailText":"<p>It is an MG, but not as you know it… The romantic old roadster is now a&nbsp;cheap supermini – but it's not all bad, says <strong>Martin Love</strong></p>","allowUgc":"false","headline":"MG3: car review","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"Martin Love","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/12/19/1387456355130/MG3-003.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","newspaperPageNumber":"50","internalStoryPackageCode":"49569","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-01T10:30:00Z","standfirst":"It is an MG, but not as you know it… The romantic old roadster is now a&nbsp;cheap supermini – but it's not all bad","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2014-05-22T11:10:45Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/dec/29/mg3-car-review-martin-love","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/technology/2013/dec/29/mg3-car-review-martin-love","sectionName":"Technology","tags":[{"id":"technology/series/wheels","webTitle":"Wheels","description":"Martin Love covers new models, developments in the motoring industry and quirky tales from the highways and byways of the world of transport","type":"series","sectionId":"technology","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/